<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Northern chambers report steady economic growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, JAMES BUXTON and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The business climate is improving steadily across most of the north of
England and Scotland but export performance is patchy and mid-term
confidence has fallen in the north-east, a clutch of surveys showed
yesterday.
The surveys, by three chambers of commerce, suggest that Scottish companies
are the most optimistic in the northerly regions.
Economic recovery is strengthening in Scotland with business confidence
rising in all sectors except retailing, and demand increasing faster than in
the first quarter of the year, according to the Scottish chambers of
commerce.
Optimism rose in the Scottish construction industry on the back of a modest
rise in orders from the private sector, but orders in the public sector
remained a cause of concern. Business improved in the tourism and leisure
sectors.
There is a significant rise in confidence among Scottish manufacturers,
which reported a strong increase in sales and orders.
This picture was at odds with surveys in north and north-east England, which
both reported poorer export conditions.
A quarterly survey by the Northern Development Company in association with
the Teesside and Tyne and Wear Chambers of Commerce says companies in the
north-east and Cumbria found improvements in UK sales and orders as well as
export sales in the second quarter.
There has been a fall in export orders, however, and in investment in plant,
machinery and buildings. The survey shows business confidence in the medium
term falling.
A quarterly survey by Sheffield and Rotherham chamber of commerce and
industry was slightly more upbeat.
Companies said that demand and output were showing continuous, if uneven,
growth in domestic markets.
More than half of the manufacturers in the survey reported rising sales in
the second quarter, compared with the first quarter of the year, when 42 per
cent said sales were up. Order books are growing, although export markets
were disappointing.
</TEXT>
