<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Tecs 'more keen' to merge with chambers: FT survey of
training chiefs finds frustration with Whitehall links
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Directors of Training and Enterprise Councils have shown a sharp increase in
their willingness to merge with chambers of commerce, an annual survey by
the Financial Times shows.
The survey is the third to canvass the 1,220 board members of the 82 Tecs in
England and Wales, which are responsible for delivering the government's
main training programmes. The annual conference of Tec directors opened in
Birmingham last night and was addressed by Mr David Hunt, employment
secretary, and Mr John Prescott, shadow employment secretary.
About 47 per cent of directors backed mergers between Tecs and chambers of
commerce, with 45 per cent against. In 1992 just 20 per cent supported such
a move.
The trend is indicative of a greater willingness by Tecs to work with
partners, and their growing involvement in providing business help. Several
Tecs now have a formal commitment to merging with chambers.
But most Tec directors expressed frustration over their lack of independence
from the government.
A total of 71 one per cent said that they did not believe that Tecs - an
experiment in partnership between the government and the private sector -
were sufficiently independent of the government.
The government is one of the main customers of Tecs and pays them more than
Pounds 2bn a year to administer publicly funded training programmes and to
foster enterprise.
The government has also fostered closer links between Tecs and chambers,
particularly through Business Links, the new umbrella bodies for business
advice in which Tecs work with agencies including chambers.
Tec directors, most of whom come from the private sector, this year
expressed even stronger support for the promotion of economic development as
their top priority. Support is also growing among trade union and
public-sector members.
Directors said strategies for economic development took up more time than
managing government programmes for the adult unemployed and young people.
However, in spite of reforms - such as the new integrated regional offices,
which co-ordinate policy at local level for several government departments -
66 per cent of directors said Whitehall was not properly co-ordinating its
work with Tecs.
The government is still attempting to strike a balance between making Tecs
publicly accountable and giving them the freedom they say they need to
operate effectively.
New three-year licensing agreements to be issued to Tecs meeting tough
criteria are to be rolled out over the next few years, and should assuage
some frustration.
The need for Tecs to be seen as accountable to their wider public is an
issue that has been taken up by a number of bodies, including the
Confederation of British Industry.
A total of 83 per cent said Tecs should be open to public scrutiny, with the
private-sector members recording the lowest support for such a policy, at 78
per cent.
Asked how this aim could be furthered, directors suggested open annual
general meetings, more open days and Tec membership schemes. A few advocated
a change in board composition, to include more local authority
representatives. One director suggested full public scrutiny of all grants
greater than Pounds 50,000.
A greater willingness to work with other bodies operating in the fields of
enterprise was expressed.
FT 1994 Survey of Tecs. Marketing Department, Financial Times, 1 Southwark
Bridge, London SE1 9HL. Pounds 6.
Editorial comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
