<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / PM tells water chiefs to limit pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Directors of privatised water companies should abide by the government's
strict limits on pay increases for public-sector workers, Mr John Major said
yesterday.
During rowdy Commons exchanges the prime minister defended water
privatisation against repeated attacks by Mrs Margaret Beckett, the acting
Labour leader.
But he said directors of privatised utilities 'should follow the lead which
the government has set for pay in the public sector and elsewhere'.
Guidelines announced last September by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor,
froze the public-sector pay bill, but allowed pay increases backed by
productivity improvements.
Mr Major's comments reflect growing sensitivity among ministers about water
bills and rising salaries, which were an important issue during the European
and local elections.
The question-time row followed publication by the National Consumer Council
of a report saying that domestic water bills had risen by 67 per cent since
privatisation.
Mrs Beckett said that privatisation had turned into 'a swindle, licensed
theft and legalised robbery' of British families. 'How can you defend the
fact that the chairman of North West Water got Pounds 47,000 a year before
privatisation and now he gets Pounds 338,000?'.
Letters, Page 22
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
