<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Clarke pitches for 'hard centre'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke yesterday joined ideological battle with Mr Tony Blair,
front-runner for the Labour leadership, with a pledge that the Conservatives
would occupy the 'hard centre' of British politics.
In a speech staking out the territory on which the two main parties will
fight the next general election, the chancellor warned his rightwing Tory
colleagues that the party had to respond to the new insecurities of the
middle classes.
The increasing numbers facing temporary unemployment as the economy changed
wanted to know that there was a high-quality health and education system on
which their families could depend.
The middle manager from middle England also wanted to know that there was a
'modernised, affordable welfare system which will assist him with the means
to retrain and find new employment'.
But Mr Clarke was equally adamant that Britain could not escape the
realities of the intensified competition of global markets. 'Stop the world,
I want to get off' was simply not an option, he said.
He added that alongside the security of the welfare state both the least
well-off and the citizens of middle England wanted to keep 'more of every
extra pound they earn or save'. That meant a sustained squeeze on public
spending and further cuts in marginal tax rates.
In his lecture at the London School of Economics to the Social Market
Foundation, he dismissed the idea that markets and social stability were
inevitably in conflict and said Labour was engaged in a desperate struggle
to come to terms with market forces. For all Mr Blair's talk of a 'dynamic
market economy' the opposition still depended on the notion of 'collective
power' to assist the individual.
The lecture brought an immediate attack from Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow
chancellor, who accused Mr Clarke of 'panicking in the face of renewed
confidence on the left'. Mr Brown said recognition by the government that
crude free market theory had had its day would be greeted by the electorate
with a mixture of 'amusement and incredulity'.
Mr Clarke flatly rejected the argument that belief in market forces led to
an atomisation of society and corroded the nation's institutions. Instead he
insisted that by harnessing market signals in areas such as health,
education and police, the government was strengthening the welfare state.
The chancellor said the task of the government was to explain that 'our
agenda will continue to reconcile free market principles with an enlightened
social policy. Free market principles underwrite institutions, they do not
undermine them'.
He added that market principles such as choice and accountability
strengthened the local institutions which bound together individuals.
Reforms in the health, education and police services reinforced the sense of
'ownership' on the part of local citizens. Such an approach combined the
best of the Conservatives' One Nation tradition with Thatcherite
determination.
</TEXT>
<XX>
