<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Minister confirms contact with BR
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, said at the Commons employment
committee yesterday that he had told members of the British Rail board on
June 9 that Railtrack's 5.7 per cent interim pay offer to the RMT transport
union conflicted with government guidelines.
However, Mr MacGregor denied he was involved in the 'details' of
negotiation. In a written memorandum to the committee, the Department of
Transport said that it had been made clear to Railtrack that any increases
in pay for signal workers had to be 'offset by improvements in efficiency
and productivity and the package must represent value for money'.
During his session with the committee Mr MacGregor said he hoped the two
sides would return to negotiations and there could be an early settlement of
the dispute.
He pointed out that signalling staff had enjoyed a 47 per cent real
improvement in their earnings since 1980 and benefited from the introduction
of new technology and increased investment. This compared with a 37 per cent
increase in real earnings for all manual workers in the country.
Yesterday's talks at Acas brought only a Pounds 50 improvement in
Railtrack's offer of a one-off cash payment. The RMT said Railtrack had
refused to add that sum to basic pay rates, while the company replied that
its offer was only an opening one. The union wants the company to increase
the size of the pay package from an overall figure of Pounds 4.3m. 'The
costs appear to be set in concrete, mixed at Department of Transport
headquarters in Marsham Street,' said Mr Knapp.
There are no plans for further talks.
</TEXT>
