<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Mandarins angered by ministerial numbers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Whitehall's mandarins are up in arms. They have too many ministerial
masters.
On the eve of a white paper foreshadowing more cuts in civil-servant
numbers, the mandarins are complaining that ministers have exempted
themselves from the Conservative drive to reduce the size of the state.
A handful of optimists in Whitehall are suggesting that Mr John Major, the
prime minister, might use the forthcoming reshuffle to practise what the
government preaches and cut the number of jobs for the boys - and girls.
Realists predict the prime minister will be more concerned to maintain the
fragile peace on the Tory back benches, so patronage will again come before
principle.
The Treasury estimates that privatisation and contracting out has cut the
size of the government by about a quarter since the start of the Thatcher
revolution in 1979.
Civil-service numbers have fallen 24 per cent from 732,000 to 554,000.
Today's white paper will forecast another fall to below 500,000.
But ministers have made sure that they are insulated from the chill winds of
competition. Comparison of the official lists shows that there were 81
ministers and 21 paid government whips in Mrs Margaret Thatcher's first
administration. Now there are 87 ministers and the same number of whips.
If these well-heeled ministers had suffered the same squeeze as their
mandarins, the number chauffeured to and from their plush offices at
taxpayer's expense would have fallen to a mere 62.
The cost is not borne only by the taxpayer. Superfluous ministers add to the
workload of their civil servants. Each demands a private office of
high-flying officials. Many more are deployed in keeping them out of
mischief or finding them something to do.
A random survey of top officials yesterday revealed that the problem is
spread right across the government. For all his managerial expertise Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, apparently needs six
ministers to help him spend one of the smallest budgets in Whitehall.
At the Treasury Sir Terence Burns, the permanent secretary, has slashed the
number of top officials. But Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, has four
ministerial helpers.
The Department of Transport has separate ministers for roads and for public
transport in spite of its promise of an integrated transport policy. At
Environment Mr John Gummer has five middle-ranking and junior ministers to
help him contemplate the future of the planet.
Nor can these myriad parliamentary under-secretaries, ministers of state,
solicitors-general and economic secretaries claim their Westminster
workloads have increased. Responses to MPs questions more often than not
consist of referrals to the relevant agency or privatised business.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
