<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Football clubs to confer over tax probe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Football Association's Premier League has called a meeting of leading
clubs to help co-ordinate their response to a tax investigation by the
Inland Revenue's Special Office - the arm of the Revenue that carries out
special probes.
The agenda for the meeting, to be held in London on August 9, includes
discussions of loans to players, payments to agents, testimonial matches for
players and relocation expenses.
In a letter to the clubs Mr Rick Parry, the Premier League's chief
executive, recommends that they do not grant the Revenue full access to
records and players' files.
He says: 'You should be aware that the working party advisers are unanimous
in the view that it is preferable to undertake your own review, rather than
allow Special Office unrestricted access.'
The FA recently fined Tottenham Hotspur, the London Premier League club,
Pounds 1.5m, deducted six league points for next season and banned it from
the season's FA Cup competition after deciding that it had contravened FA
rules by making interest-free loans to players between 1985 and 1989.
Tottenham says it has settled with the Revenue and will not be at the
meeting.
However, the Premier League's efforts on behalf of clubs being investigated
is said to have 'hardened the resolve' of Mr Alan Sugar, Tottenham chairman,
to fight the penalty, possibly with legal action.
One football insider said: 'It's amazing that the FA hands down such a stiff
fine for things that went on before Sugar took over at Spurs and then we see
the Premier League arranging a meeting to help other clubs facing a Revenue
investigation.'
</TEXT>
