<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Council shake-up plans defy Gummer view
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Local Government Commission for England yesterday repeated its
recommendation that most of County Durham should keep a two-tier structure
of local government, in spite of the refusal from Mr John Gummer, the
environment secretary, to accept this proposal when it was first made last
year.
Mr Gummer said he expected all-purpose unitary authorities, combining the
functions of both district and county councils, to emerge from the review.
The commission's refusal to alter its position is seen to signal its
independence from the government.
Its recommendation, following a second review of opinion in the area, is
that Darlington should have unitary status, with the rest of the county
covered by the county council and seven districts.
Lead commissioners Mrs Ann Levick and Mr David Ansbro denied that the
commission was challenging Mr Gummer and his enthusiasm for unitary
authorities. Mrs Levick said: 'We are required to find out what local people
want. It will be seen as an assertion of the commission carrying out its
remit, within the terms of the guidance.'
The commission, she added, was independent. 'I have broad shoulders. I have
no problem with flak.'
During the second review the commission received fewer than 100
representations, some of them questioning the need for the second review.
This compared with 27,900 after its first review, of which only 12 per cent
favoured a unitary district option.
Mr Allan Roberts, chief executive of Sedgefield district council, which
campaigned for unitary authorities, criticised the decision.
He said: 'If the review's just going to be tinkering around with those
authorities which are unpopular one has to question whether the whole
exercise has been a waste of money.'
The two-tier system is an option in both East and West Sussex under
proposals published yesterday. The commission's preferred option would see
unitary authorities in the east of the county, with two-tiers in the west.
Both Brighton and a new authority merging the coastal districts of Hove,
Adur and Worthing would become unitaries under all recommendations put
forward. The preferred option for the rest of West Sussex is the two-tier
system, while for East Sussex the commission suggests merging Eastbourne and
Lewes with south Wealden including Uckfield, and Hastings and Rother with
the rest of Wealden.
The commission believes the plan for West Sussex could save 'up to Pounds
2m' a year and would cost up to Pounds 6m to implement. The unitary plan for
East Sussex would be more expensive, costing between Pounds 22m and Pounds
25m to implement, with annual savings of between Pounds 2m and Pounds 7m.
As alternatives, the commission suggests East Sussex outside Brighton should
remain two-tier, cutting start-up costs to between Pounds 5m and Pounds 7m.
West Sussex outside the coastal strip could be split into two unitaries,
combining Arun - including Bognor Regis - with Chichester, and Crawley and
Horsham with Mid-Sussex. But this option would cost between Pounds 22m and
Pounds 24m to set up, with lower annual savings, potentially as little as
Pounds 1m.
</TEXT>
