FT  13 JUL 94 / French go-ahead for reactor
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The French government yesterday gave the go-ahead to a consortium of
European energy companies to restart the controversial Superphenix
fast-breeder nuclear reactor for research purposes. The reactor, near Lyons,
in eastern France, was shut in July 1990 because of technical faults in its
fuel cooling systems. The plant will be used to study how to get rid of
plutonium and other radioactive waste from France's 56 nuclear reactors.
Environmental groups have opposed the restart of the reactor, but the French
government has said the reactor could be restarted at limited power after
safety work. Superphenix is operated by the Nersa consortium, which includes
Electricite de France, Enel of Italy and SBK of Germany.
