   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Sir Iain Vallance, chairman of British Telecommunications, will call tonight
for a single EU telecommunications regulator in a move set to intensify the
debate on the future role of Brussels in a liberalised telecoms industry.
Acknowledging 'ideological' objections to an increase in EU regulatory
powers, Sir Iain claims that it is nonetheless 'difficult to see' how any
other regime could ensure fair telecoms competition across the EU. The call
comes at a critical stage in the EU telecoms liberalisation process. The
Corfu heads of government summit last month agreed to an acceleration in the
pace of telecommunications liberalisation, in particular by opening
infrastructure to competition, instead of services alone as previously
agreed. In his speech to the European Policy Forum, Sir Iain says: 'a level
playing field requires a pan-European regulatory regime, properly enforced
by a well-balanced, pan-European regulator.'
