<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Brussels softens lineon film, TV quotas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A senior European Commission official yesterday signalled that Brussels
intended to take a more lenient approach to regulating the European film and
television industry, forecasting that quotas designed to protect the sector
could become a thing of the past because of rapid technological change.
Mr Reinhard Buscher, a member of the cabinet of Commissioner Martin
Bangemann, told a Financial Times multi- media conference in London that the
development of video-on-demand, pay-per-view services made quotas an old
battle which would be less and less important.
There have been furious rows between the US film and television industries
over quotas which have been designed to protect the European production
industries.
'Entertainment is becoming more and more an economic good that we should pay
for individually without any harm to culture or languages,' said Mr Buscher,
who said that his personal approach on quotas was shared by Mr Bangemann.
At the moment, European Union legislation means that broadcasters have to
have a majority of European programme content where practicable.
Although Commission officials concede privately that quotas are difficult to
enforce, the official line - at least until now - has been that they are
necessary to protect European culture and to nurture the audiovisual
industry.
Mr Buscher's comments add to gradual indications that the Commission is
willing to consider changes to the broadcasting directive. However, they are
likely to anger countries such as France, which are strongly in favour of
quotas.
He added, though, that free movement for US programmes would have to be
balanced by measures to support the European film and television industries.
The Brussels approach to creating an 'information society' was to stimulate
practical applications using existing funds rather than seeking a single
solution, said Mr Buscher.
The Commission is expected to announce an action plan next week which is
designed to implement main the recommendations of the Bangemann report on
the information society.
These range from teleworking and distance learning to creation of networks
for universities and research centres and health care to a trans-European
public administration network.
'Research projects and experimental applications must now be taken out of
the laboratories into real life so they become social and economic realities
in order to create new markets and new job opportunities,' Mr Buscher said.
</TEXT>
