<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / BR aims for 3,000 strike-breaking trains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR and ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Railtrack will today make its most concerted effort yet to break the
signalling strike, with 3,000 trains running - about 50 per cent more than
during the last one-day strike a week ago.
The strike will be the fifth consecutive Wednesday stoppage in an
increasingly bitter dispute. RMT, the transport union, meets tomorrow to
consider stepping up action after talks called to settle the dispute failed
early on Tuesday.
Railtrack is confident it can position its small number of working signalmen
where they will have the greatest impact. It believes that in some areas it
will in effect break the strike. The company, responsible for track, signals
and stations, has tried to press every supervisor and manager into operating
signal boxes. That may enable British Rail to run a fifth of its normal
weekday services.
Trains expected to run today which did not run last Wednesday include the
InterCity express services between Euston and Birmingham International and
suburban services from Woking and Hampton Court to Waterloo.
Other strike-breaking services will include commuter trains on north
Merseyside, between Liverpool and Southport; between Bristol and Salisbury;
and in north Wales from Llandudno to Blaenau Ffestiniog.
A Railtrack executive said: 'The strike is pretty well broken in some parts
of the country, though it is rock solid in others.'
BR believes there is little scope for further services if the stoppage
continues.
RMT blamed government interference for the collapse of negotiations. Mr
Jimmy Knapp, the union's general secretary, suggested that Railtrack, wholly
owned by the government, was still not free to negotiate with the RMT on
past productivity.
Mr Knapp said: 'The real difference between the two sides is not great. But
the government has to take the arm-lock off Railtrack's negotiators and let
them conclude a deal which they think is in the best interests of the
industry - not the political interests of the government.
'This dispute is only complex and intractable because the government has
made it so,' he added.
Mr John MacGregor, the transport secretary, confirmed yesterday to the House
of Commons employment committee that he had made clear to Railtrack that it
must negotiate with the signalling staff inside the guidelines of the
government's public sector pay freeze policy.
Signal workers reach turning point, Page 9
Observer, Page 23
</TEXT>
