<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / US telecoms group launches bid worth Dollars 2.2bn for QVC
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Comcast, the US telecoms group, last night launched a Dollars 2.2bn (Pounds
1.4bn) bid for QVC, the US television shopping group which last week agreed
to a similarly valued merger with CBS, the broadcast television network.
The Comcast bid, made in a letter to QVC chairman Mr Barry Diller, involves
an offer of Dollars 37 a share cash and Dollars 7 a share in Comcast
convertible preferred stock for all of QVC's outstanding shares. Under the
terms of the bid, Comcast is willing to pay a 22.2 per cent premium on the
current value of QVC shares, which closed last night at Dollars 36.
Comcast's offer came after the close of trading in New York.
Comcast, which is a founding shareholder in QVC, said it was making a rival
bid because it believed the proposed merger between QVC and CBS was not in
the best interests of Comcast shareholders. Comcast currently owns 15.4 per
cent of QVC on a fully diluted basis.
The funding for Comcast's offer will come from the Bank of New York, which
has told the company it can obtain commitments for a Dollars 1bn senior
credit facility, and from other sources to be arranged.
QVC officials were not available for comment last night, but it is likely
that Mr Diller will initially reject the Comcast offer.
Although the value of Comcast's bid is essentially the same as that of the
QVC-CBS deal, Comcast said last night the difference between the two
transactions was that it would not require QVC to pay any break-up fees if
the Comcast merger failed.
In the letter to Mr Diller, Comcast said QVC's board, which was scheduled to
meet today to discuss the CBS merger, should lay both bids on the table, and
submit the competing offers for consideration by a committee of independent
directors.
The rival offer from Comcast is unlikely to come as as surprise to Wall
Street. When CBS and QVC announced their merger plans last week, analysts
said that the proposed deal had in effect put both companies in play,
although industry experts had expected any new bids to have been made for
CBS, not QVC.
The battle over the CBS-QVC merger comes against a background of major
consolidation in the US cable and broadcast television industry, which is
becoming rapidly dominated by a few large operators.
</TEXT>
