<HEADLINE>
FT  13 JUL 94 / Rosyth naval base wins reprieve as MoD saves Pounds 1.2bn:
Cuts in R&amp;D secure majority of 1,300 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Rosyth naval base in Fife has been saved and the majority of its 1,300
civilian workers will keep their jobs, Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence
secretary, will announce tomorrow.
Mr Rifkind will disclose that he has met the Treasury's demands for
substantial expenditure cuts by finding savings in other areas of the
defence budget, particularly research and development.
The number of redundancies at Rosyth is yet to be finalised. But MPs have
been told that most of the civilian personnel will keep their jobs, and the
number of redundances could be as low as 300.
The base has been saved in large part because the Ministry of Defence has
found it is spending about Pounds 500m more on research and development than
it had originally thought. Defence chiefs are thought to have blamed
accounting errors for the over-estimate of R&amp;D spending, which government
accountants had initially put at Pounds 800m a year. Much of the extra
Pounds 500m of spending has been judged to be unnecessary.
Mr Rifkind will also announce substantial savings have been reaped through
changes in the procurement of spare parts and ammunition. Instead of
stockpiling weapons and ammunition the armed forces will purchase more on a
'just-in-time' basis as they are required.
Taken together the savings over the next three years will help the MoD to
cut its Pounds 23.49bn a year budget by at least Pounds 1.2bn, the figure
set by the Treasury in the last budget.
There had been strong expectations that the expenditure cuts would lead to
job losses in the armed forces of between 20,000 and 25,000 - but MPs have
been told this week that the redundancies will be 'at the low end of
expectations'.
According to Downing Street, the MoD's plans for defence expenditure - set
out in a defence spending white paper dubbed 'Front Line First' - are
certain to be approved by the cabinet at its weekly meeting tomorrow.
However, MPs have been told that the white paper's plans will not be set in
concrete and will leave open the opportunity for further refinement over the
next three months.
The proposal that Rosyth should be saved follows intense last-minute
lobbying by Scottish Tory MPs, the Labour leadership and workers at the
yard.
However, Mr Rifkind is expected to announce that Rosyth will have a
different role from the one it has had in the past. According to one MoD
source, the base will concentrate on its role in minesweeping support and
fisheries protection. The base will also remain available for military
emergencies.
On Monday, Mr Rifkind appeared to give slight hope to Rosyth when he
attacked Labour's 'hysterical outpourings' about the future of the Fife
base. He said the decision on Rosyth would be made 'in a sensitive,
thoughtful fashion'.
However, Mr Gordon Brown, shadow chancellor, has kept up a campaign to
maintain the base, which is in his constituency.
Earlier this week, he revealed that he had received a confidential Royal
Navy study which described Rosyth as 'ideal' with 'excellent facilities' and
'the only area that can fully meet the the requirements and demands' of
minesweepers.
Workers lobby parliament: picture, Page 10
</TEXT>
