<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / RAI board named after coalition row
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The heads of Italy's two houses of parliament last night named a new
five-member board of directors for Italy's state broadcasting organisation,
the RAI, following a row over the appointments between the coalition
partners in the right-wing government.
The announcement was made by Mr Carlo Scognamiglio, the Senate speaker, and
Ms Irene Pivetti, his counterpart in the lower house, the Chamber of
Deputies. Ms Pivetti, a member of the populist Northern League - one of the
coalition members - was instrumental in blocking the first board list
presented.
Prime Minister Silvio Berlusconi, through last night's announcement, appears
to have acted quickly to limit the damage from a dispute that had threatened
his own authority. He had not wished to be seen making too many concessions
to the individual interests of the coalition partners and, at Naples at the
weekend, where he attended the Group of Seven summit, he refused the call
for a special coalition meeting to discuss the RAI board.
The new board members have apparently been chosen for their management flair
and are representative of both the League and Forza Italia, another
coalition member and the party of Mr Berlusconi.
The five include Mr Ennio Presutti, head of the Assolombarda industrialists'
association in Lombardy, academic Mr Franco Cardini, and Mr Mauro Miccio,
head of Asca news agency. The list is completed by businessman Mr Alfio
Marchini and Ms Letizia Brichetti Moratti, head of the insurance brokers'
association.
The dispute had centred on moves by Forza Italia, the League and the
neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance, the third coalition partner, to ensure
they all had their own nominees represented on the board of what continues
to be Italy's most influential media network. This is a classic example of
the fights to carve up influence in a state body which so discredited
successive post-war governments and which Mr Berlusconi himself has sought
to avoid.
The one-year-old RAI board was forced to step down on June 30 following the
government's threat to refuse to accept its financial reorganisation plan
and emergency funding. The members, though installed as technicians, were
considered too close to the previous governing parties. But the government
had previously been critical of the RAI's bias against Mr Berlusconi.
</TEXT>
