<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Equities steady despite
weaker bond market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Although the dollar plunged again on foreign exchange markets yesterday, US
share prices held their own in the face of the rapidly declining US currency
and a weaker bond market, writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close, the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 6.15 at 3,702.99
well above its low for the day of 3,680.33. The more broadly based Standard
&amp; Poor's 500 ended down 1.49 at 448.06, while the American Stock Exchange
composite finished off 0.68 at 424.77 and the Nasdaq composite down 0.63 at
706.83. Trading volume on the NYSE was light at 224m shares.
Stock prices took their cue from the bond market in early trading. After
firming slightly at the opening, stocks soon retreated as bonds posted
modest losses. The quarter-point decline in the benchmark 30-year bond was
sparked by higher commodities prices and further declines in the dollar. By
late afternoon the US currency was down at a new post-1945 low against the
Yen of Y97.65, and below the DM1.53 against the D-mark for the first time
since November, 1992.
The fall in the dollar unsettled bonds because fixed-income investors feared
it would persuade the Federal Reserve that interest rates would have to go
up to protect the ailing currency. The drop in bonds, however, was not
especially disturbing, and the resilience of fixed-income investors appeared
to buoy stock market sentiment. Both bonds and stocks were helped by the
opinion of analysts that Fed would not make a decision on whether to tighten
monetary policy until after the release of the June inflation figures today
and tomorrow. Among individual stocks, McKesson was the star of the show,
soaring Dollars 24 1/2 , or 33 per cent, to Dollars 97 5/8 in volume of 3.2m
shares after drugs group Eli Lilly agreed to buy McKesson's retail drug
distribution subsidiary, PCS Health, for Dollars 4bn in cash. The news,
however, was not so well received by Eli Lilly shareholders: the company's
stock dropped Dollars 7 3/8 to Dollars 50.
Caterpillar continued to be the stock of choice among cyclically-minded
investors. Cyclical stocks have been strong recently as buyers anticipated
improved earnings in the wake of the growing economy, but none has benefited
more than Caterpillar, which yesterday firmed another Dollars 1 5/8 to
Dollars 107 3/8 .
Dow Jones dropped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 29 1/4 in busy trading after the
financial publishing group announced second quarter net income of 46 cents a
share, up from 40 cents a share a year earlier but below the consensus of
analysts' forecasts. On the Nasdaq market, Gaming Corporation of America, a
Nasdaq-quoted stock, dropped Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 2 5/8 after the
company was denied a renewal of its licence by the Wisconsin Winnebago
gaming commission.
Canada
Toronto prices ended mixed in moderate trading, despite higher gold stocks.
The TSE-300 composite index added 5.04 points, or 0.12 per cent, to close at
4,103.94, although losing issues led winners by 394 to 325.
Volume of 42.06m shares was down from 45.82m last Friday, and trading value
was CDollars 515.5m compared with CDollars 567.5m.
Northern Telecom was downgraded to intermediate-term neutral from above
average by Merrill Lynch. The company also announced a Dollars 100m cellular
system contract in Taiwan. The stock fell 3/8 to 40 7/8.
</TEXT>
