<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Government Bonds: US Treasuries fall in wake of weaker
dollar
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON and CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US Treasury prices fell across the maturity range yesterday in the wake of
higher commodities prices and another plunge in the value of the dollar.
In late trading, the benchmark 30-year government bond was down  1/4 at 83,
yielding 7.716 per cent.
In the absence of fresh economic statistics, all eyes were on the dollar
when the market opened, and it was a dollar that continued to weaken against
other major currencies.
It was not long before bonds began to slip in the dollar's wake, as the
currency slumped to a new post-1945 low against the yen of Y97.70 and to
DM1.53 against the D-Mark, its lowest level since late 1992.
The decline in the dollar undermined prices because investors believed the
Federal Reserve might be forced to raise interest rates, although most
analysts said any move was unlikely until today's and tomorrow's June
inflation figures had been released.
A rise in commodities prices further undermined bonds, although the increase
in the Commodity Research Bureau's closely-followed index was attributed by
analysts to a surge in coffee prices following news of a bad frost in
Brazil.
As the dollar continued to tumble, portfolio shifts into Europe's safe
havens out of US Treasuries bolstered European bond markets.
'After the G7 failed to offer a package in support of the dollar, there now
seems to be less danger in allocating funds to Europe,' said Mr Chris
Anthony, head of fixed interest research at Hoare Govett.
While some traders reported large shifts in cash bonds by institutional
investors, others said cash activity remained thin, with most of the action
taking place in the futures pits. This spurred talk that hedge funds, which
are often active in the futures markets, were behind some of the buying.
Over the last two trading sessions, European bonds have shrugged off sharp
declines in US bonds. 'The markets' resilience on Friday and yesterday has
reawakened the issue of decoupling between US and European yields,' noted Mr
Stephen Dulake, bond strategist at PaineWebber in London.
However, he added that 'we haven't seen this uptrend confirmed by investor
sponsorship, and I feel there are still many reasons to be cautious.'
Mr Dulake said it was unlikely that European bond yields could fall on a
sustainable basis unless US bonds recover or at least stabilise.
Several key US statistics are due this week, and 'there's a strong risk that
further declines in the US could undermine European bonds', he warned.
French bonds rose sharply yesterday, outperforming their German counterparts
after underperforming them last week. The September notional French
government bond future on Matif rose by 1.12 points to 115.68.
Sentiment was boosted by positive data, showing June inflation unchanged at
1.8 per cent year-on-year, and by foreign buying, traders said. Moreover,
last week's successful bond auction has lent the market a healthier tone, a
dealer said.
UK gilts also had a strong day, boosted by buoyant continental European
markets and overseas investor buying. The September long gilt futures
contract on Liffe rose by points to 101 3/4 .
The market was further cheered by a Gallup report of leading UK investment
funds for Smith New Court, which showed that many fund managers are becoming
increasingly bullish about gilts and view the market's recent weakness as a
buying opportunity.
German government bonds also benefited from the flight to safety by
investors. The September bund futures contract on Liffe rose by 0.83 points
to 93.32.
</TEXT>
