<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / International Company News: Debt reduction helps lift net at
France Telecom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France Telecom, the state-owned telecommunications operator, yesterday
announced a sharp jump in net profits for last year, to FFr4.8bn (Dollars
888.8m) from FFr3.3bn in 1992.
The increase was achieved on a slight rise in sales, from FFr122.6bn to
FFr127bn, and reflected a fall in financial charges as the operator pursued
a policy of debt-reduction.
At the end of last year, group borrowings were down to FFr105.6bn, compared
with FFr111.6bn at the same time in 1992.
As a result, financial charges fell to 6.9 per cent of sales, against 8.4
per cent the previous year. There was a FFr15.2bn payment to the state, the
same as in 1992.
France Telecom said the rise in sales, which confirmed its position as the
world's fourth-largest telecoms group after NTT of Japan, Deutsche Telekom
and AT&amp;T of the US, was achieved against a background of depressed demand in
France.
Considering the difficult environment, it said the improved revenues
reflected the impact of new products such as Itineris and Bi-Bop, its mobile
telephone services.
Itineris, which operates a mobile radio-telephone service, had 78,700
subscribers at the end of last year. Meanwhile, Bi-Bop, which requires the
user to be near a base station, had 38,000 subscribers. Both services have
seen strong growth.
The group also saw continued growth in its Minitel teletext activities.
Subscriptions rose to 6.5m from 6.3m, while the number of services available
on Minitel rose to 23,000.
France Telecom plans to pursue its strategy of reducing debt, while seeking
partnerships in its core telecommunications activities, and in new areas
such as multimedia.
Last month, it announced the formation of a partnership with Deutsche
Telekom and Sprint of the US to provide services to multinational clients.
This represented an extension of the French operator's existing alliance
with Deutsche Telekom, agreed in 1993.
The alliances do not yet involve equity participations, partly because of
France Telecom's public-sector status.
Plans to reform this status, a necessary step before any eventual
privatisation, have been delayed while the proposal is discussed with
unions.
</TEXT>
