<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Tomkins jumps 50% to Pounds 257m: Chief executive finds
share price 'depressing' but foresees further acquisitions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WIGHTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gregory Hutchings, chief executive of Tomkins, yesterday expressed
astonishment at the industrial conglomerate's low share price after it
announced a better-than-expected 50 per cent jump in pre-tax profits to
Pounds 257m. 'We win every match and we are still bottom of the league,' he
said.
He pointed to the 14 per cent increase in earnings per share to 15.1p in the
year to April, compared with a UK average of 6 per cent. Yet the shares have
underperformed the market by almost 30 per cent since it announced its
Pounds 990m bid for Ranks Hovis McDougall in October 1992. They rose just
1/2 p to 218p yesterday.
The RHM businesses contributed profits of Pounds 102.5m and enhanced
earnings per share by 'at least' 4 per cent despite a bitter price war in
the volume bread market. 'We have always delivered to shareholders what we
said we would, which is what makes the share price so depressing,' said Mr
Hutchings.
He added that the lowly share rating would not prevent the group taking
advantage of acquisition opportunities. 'With a very strong balance sheet we
could gear up if we saw a major acquisition.' He stressed that nothing was
presently being contemplated and any large deal would be outside its main
businesses. 'We like being a diversified company.'
Dividends rose 16 per cent to 7.38p, after a final payment of 5.3p, which Mr
Hutchings said reflected the group's strong cash flow and good growth
prospects. 'We are very optimistic and excited about the future. We are in
the best position we have ever been.' He said that the integration of RHM
was largely going to plan although delays in the delivery of capital
equipment had pushed back the rationalisation programme. It has spent Pounds
23.3m out of the Pounds 81.2m provision set up for reorganisation.
Profits from milling and baking rose to Pounds 22.1m on sales of Pounds
682.2m - compared with a 21-week contribution of Pounds 1.4m on turnover of
Pounds 287.9m the previous year - but return on capital employed was still
'unsatisfactory'. The Mr Kipling cakes business has been disappointing and
bread baking suffered from the price war, which Tomkins estimated had cost
the main supermarket chains more than Pounds 50m in the last nine months.
Profits from food products rose to Pounds 80.4m on turnover of Pounds
939.5m, against Pounds 28.4m on sales of Pounds 374.9m, and Mr Hutchings
said there was 'a lot more still to come'.
Profits from the non-food businesses rose 13 per cent to Pounds 130.6m on
turnover of Pounds 1.62bn (Pounds 1.32bn). US housing and housing-related
activities had a second year of 'solid growth'. The lawnmowers business
performed well, but bicycle margins suffered from the threat of Chinese
competition.
Tomkins generates half its profits in dollars and a hedged rate of Dollars
1.59, compared with Dollars 1.76m the previous year, added about 4.5 per
cent to sterling profits on translation. This year's rate is Dollars 1.48,
giving it a gain of more than 3 per cent.
The company said the UK was at last showing some signs of emerging from
recession with companies serving the light engineering and housing markets
seeing some pick-up.
Tomkins ended the year with net cash of Pounds 156m, after spending Pounds
100m on the acquisition of Noma Industries, and shareholders' funds rose to
Pounds 897.8m (Pounds 802.0m).
Broker Hoare Govett forecasts profits of Pounds 300m this year with earnings
up 19 per cent at 17.9p.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
