<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Revenue moves on charity tax clause
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Inland Revenue acted quickly yesterday to stave off a mistaken
interpretation of law which would have forced many charities operating
lotteries to pay additional tax.
In a parliamentary written answer, Sir John Cope, the paymaster-general,
said the Revenue had received advice that a technique used by charities to
set off lottery income against tax was 'incorrect'.
The change affects all charities that operated a lottery through a
subsidiary company which passed on the income through a deed of covenant.
Until now, the Revenue believed it was acceptable to use this structure
under section 5 of the 1976 Lotteries and Amusements Act to set the lottery
income against tax.
Its new advice suggests that the income from the lottery belongs to the
charity rather than to the subsidiary and the charity is therefore taxable
on the income.
However, Sir John stressed that the government did not want charities to be
disadvantaged by the changes in the interpretation of the law.
He said new legislation would be introduced in the next finance bill to
ensure charities would be exempt from tax on the lottery income as long as
the income is applied solely to the charity.
He said small lotteries operated under section 3 of the 1976 act would also
be exempted. The amendment would apply for accounting periods after March 31
next year.
</TEXT>
