<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Hurd issues plea over EU entrants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, appealed to Tory Euro-sceptics in the
Commons last night not to oppose the bill enabling Britain to agree the
entry of Sweden, Finland, Norway and Austria into the European Union.
He said that if their fears that the new entrants would boost the
development of the EU's social dimension proved well-founded, it would
increase the value of Britain's opt-out from the relevant section of the
Maastricht treaty.
Mr Hurd urged the Euro-sceptics not to start opposing enlargement of the EU
'simply because we do not always agree with all the views of those who come
in'.
He stressed that as Sweden, Austria and Norway would be net contributors to
the EU's budget, they would share Britain's interests in budgetary
discipline and value for money.
Mr Hurd also emphasised that as a result of the additional number of net
contributors it was expected that the UK's contribution would be some Pounds
300m less during the first six years of accession than it would otherwise
have been. Other favourable factors included the benefit to Britain's
agricultural exports through the opening of the previously protected markets
of the four applicant countries.
Producers of offshore supplies for the oil industry would benefit from
Norway's acceptance of EU rules, he said.
Mr Hurd forecast that overall British business would benefit 'not hugely but
significantly' from enlargement of the EU.
He also looked to the entrants to support the UK's drive for vigorous
application of 'subsidiarity' - ensuring that where possible decisions are
made at national level.
The European Union (Accessions) bill was given an unopposed second reading.
</TEXT>
