<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Pearson chief warns at delay on multimedia law
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government was yesterday accused of squandering the momentum behind a
multi-media revolution by delaying legislation for the foreseeable future.
Mr Frank Barlow, group managing director of Pearson, the media and
entertainment group which owns the Financial Times, warned that a couple of
years or more could be lost.
Speaking in the context of existing cross-media ownership rules, Mr Barlow
said the UK had a chance to lead the world in the media if the government
acted quickly and positively. Existing rules prevent newspapers owning more
than 20 per cent of broadcasters.
If the government did not act 'it could be hard for even the best players in
the industry to go forward as they would like to', Mr Barlow told a Media
Society lunch in London.
The danger was that even before a final set of recommendations had gone to
ministers from a committee looking into cross-media ownership rules, the
word in Whitehall was there would be no time for legislation.
If there was no time in the 1994-95 legislative programme real changes in
the 1995-96 parliamentary session could not be guaranteed because an
election would then be looming.
'So by squandering the momentum now, the government could be losing a couple
of years at least, perhaps more,' Mr Barlow said.
He added that he wanted to see the media treated like any other industry in
terms of ownership, subject to the normal rules of competition and
concentration of ownership.
Mr Barlow said he thought the barrier for individual ownership could be set
at 25 per cent of the whole market including newspaper sales and revenues
and television advertising and subscription revenues.
Such a suggestion if implemented would allow a much greater concentration of
media power than is permitted under existing legislation.
</TEXT>
