<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Church looks for finance stop-gap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An attempt is to be made to give the Church of England a longer period to
solve its financial problems by enabling the Church Commissioners to incur
negative reserves.
The Church faces serious financial difficulties following a sharp reduction
in the amount available from the commissioners' efforts.
This led to the commissioners proposing a Pounds 22m cut in their
contribution to clergy stipends and other expenditure next year. But
following complaints that this could cause permanent damage to the Church's
structure, they agreed to try to limit the 1995 reduction to Pounds 12m.
Because the commissioners are not legally empowered to run negative
reserves, the Church's General Synod was told in York yesterday that as a
last resort the gap between Pounds 22m and Pounds 12m might have to be
bridged by loans to dioceses.
Power for the commissioners to incur negative reserves would require
parliamentary approval. Some Church leaders might be unhappy to support the
proposal, as it would open up their financial problems to renewed scrutiny.
A financial crisis was generated by a Pounds 800m reduction in the value of
the commissioners' assets between 1989 and 1992, caused mainly by the
collapse of the property market.
A move to disestablish the Church from parliamentary control was defeated
last night by the Synod by 273 to 110.
</TEXT>
