<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Retention of two-tier Devon urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plymouth will have its own free-standing local authority but the rest of
Devon will keep its two-tier council structure under plans announced
yesterday by the Local Government Commission for England.
The commission's preferred option follows the pattern of other large
counties, where cities would be given unitary councils - allowing them
control over education, social services and strategic planning - while the
system of county and districts would remain intact elsewhere.
The plan would leave nine district councils working with Devon County
Council, and would cost between Pounds 2m and Pounds 6m to implement. It
would generate no savings in the longer term, the commission said.
Two alternatives which would involve abolishing the county council were also
proposed. As its second preference, the commission suggested that Plymouth,
Torbay and Exeter should all be unitary, while rural districts would be
merged to form three more unitaries: Northern Devon (including North Devon,
Torridge, and part of West Devon districts); Eastern Devon (formed by
merging East and Mid Devon districts); and Southern Devon and Dartmoor,
which would merge South Hams and Teignbridge with part of West Devon.
Costs of this option were put at Pounds 19m to Pounds 23m, with no savings
in future. However, a modification which would merge Exeter with Eastern
Devon to create five unitaries in total might save up to Pounds 5m a year,
the commission said.
Similar plans to create two new unitary authorities in Essex, based around
Southend and Basildon, while leaving the two-tier structure intact in the
rest of the county were also confirmed by the commission. It said this would
cost between Pounds 6m and Pounds 12m with no savings, while its alternative
of six unitaries would cost between Pounds 26m and Pounds 32m with annual
savings of up to Pounds 8m.
</TEXT>
<XX>
