<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / South leads rise in house prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The pace of the housing market remains very mixed, with the biggest price
rises in the south, according to a survey published yesterday by Halifax
building society.
Its quarterly survey shows that prices across northern England and Wales
have fallen on average by as much as 2.1 per cent during the past year.
The survey, which compared prices in the three months to the end of June
with those for the same period last year, showed prices had risen in seven
regions and had fallen in five. Prices increased overall by 0.6 per cent.
Halifax, the country's biggest mortgage lender, said: 'The underlying trend
in house prices in the UK is still broadly flat.
'While the market should become more buoyant as general perceptions of
economic recovery become more widespread, we do not expect annual house
price inflation to rise above 2 per cent to 3 per cent this year.'
According to the survey, prices in Northern Ireland, traditionally the
lowest in the UK, have risen 6.6 per cent in the past year. Prices in
Scotland have risen 0.4 per cent.
Halifax said that overall there was little change from last year in the
number of people searching for a new home, although there were marked
differences between regions. Demand for properties was outstripping supply
in much of southern England.
The second largest increase was in the south-east, where the average price
of a home rose 2.2 per cent to Pounds 77,360, according to the society.
It added: 'The upper end of the market, particularly in rural areas, is
reported as being the best for some time, with quick sales being achieved on
competitively priced properties.'
