<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Research agencies recommended for sell-off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two Whitehall research agencies have been recommended for privatisation in a
report published by the Cabinet Office Efficiency Unit yesterday.
The report on government research establishments recommends privatising
Adas, the farm advisory and research agency with a large agricultural
consultancy practice. The Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food is
reviewing its future. Adas was identified as a candidate for privatisation
when it became an agency in 1992.
The report also recommends privatising elements of the Building Research
Establishment, the environment department agency that carries out research
on the design, construction and performance of buildings.
If the government accepts the report's recommendations, laboratories
accounting for almost 50 per cent of such spending will be in line for
privatisation. The 50 establishments employ some 31,000 staff and cost about
Pounds 1.3bn a year to run (some of which is earned in fee income).
Research establishments not ready for privatisation should be considered for
transfer to universities or to private-sector companies, the report
recommends.
It also proposes reorganising about 30 life sciences research laboratories
into new agencies, with two options:
A geographical split, one agency for Scotland and the other for England and
Wales, with some smaller establishments being transferred to research
councils.
A four-way 'market sector' split, with agencies for marine resources,
non-marine environment, biotechnology and biological science, and food and
agriculture.
Mr William Waldegrave, science minister, said: 'I am determined to ensure
that government resources are spent to the maximum extent possible on
science rather than administrative overheads.'
The privatisation of Adas and the BRE would mean seven research agencies are
still in line for privatisation.
The others are AEA Technology, National Engineering Laboratory, Laboratory
of the Government Chemist and the Transport Research Laboratory. The
National Physical Laboratory is to become a government-owned,
contractor-operated agency.
The report was drawn up by a team of five civil servants and a part-time
member seconded from Smiths Industries, the aerospace and healthcare group.
Multi-Departmental Scrutiny of Public Sector Research Establishments. HMSO.
Pounds 15.95.
</TEXT>
