<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Fewer businesses likely to fail
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of business failures in the second quarter of the year will fall
19 per cent from the first three months, the specialist trade credit insurer
Trade Indemnity predicted yesterday.
It forecast 835 failures for the quarter, down from 1,037 in the first
quarter of this year and from 1,433 in the second quarter of last year. The
figure is expected to be the lowest quarterly total in the past three years.
Mr William Simpson, chief economist, said the drop was above expectations,
but companies were paying off their debts before embarking on further
domestic investment.
He said this could threaten their ability to increase productivity because
the cost of borrowing would increase significantly when businesses finally
do decide to invest.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
