<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Upward pressure on pay eases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Pay settlements in manufacturing fell slightly in May, easing fears of
further upward pressure on pay generated by rising inflation and tax
increases, the Confederation of British Industry said yesterday, David
Goodhart writes.
Pay awards in manufacturing averaged 2.7 per cent between March and May,
slightly down on the 2.8 per cent recorded for the three months to April.
But service-sector settlements remain at 3.2 per cent.
According to the CBI, one-third of all settlements in manufacturing and
services were between 1.5 per cent and 2.5 per cent, and overall 84 per cent
of settlements were between zero and 3.5 per cent.
Mr Howard Davies, the CBI's director-general, said: 'Manufacturers are
continuing to keep the lid on settlements, though since productivity growth
is dropping the prospect for unit labour costs is not promising. Service
settlements seem to be on the rise, especially in the financial sector. That
is not good news.'
Productivity in manufacturing improved by an average of 4.1 per cent in the
first quarter of the year compared with 4.7 per cent in the second half of
last year.
</TEXT>
