<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Brown offers plan to save Rosyth base
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, yesterday sent Mr John Major, the
prime minister, a last-minute plan which he said would enable the threatened
Rosyth naval base in Fife to survive and also save money for the government.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, is believed to be poised to announce
a further rundown or even closure of the base on the Firth of Forth when he
reveals the results of the latest defence review, probably on Thursday.
The possibility of the base closing has produced vigorous opposition from
MPs of all parties, as well as from trade unions and local government
representatives in Scotland.
Mr Brown, whose Dunfermline East constituency includes the base, proposes
that the navy locates all minesweeping activities there. This would entail
moving one squadron of six minesweepers and their support services from
Portsmouth to Rosyth, instead of transferring two squadrons of 12 ships from
Rosyth to Portsmouth, as defenders of the base believe is intended.
Mr Brown said he had devised his plan using 'detailed inside knowledge' and
'meticulously gathered expert information', including two internal navy
reports which support the case for retaining Rosyth.
He said the annual extra cost of keeping the base open had been wrongly
costed by the Ministry of Defence at Pounds 10m but was in reality Pounds
6.7m. That could be turned into a net saving of Pounds 4m: locating all
minesweeping activity at Rosyth would save Pounds 2m and concentrating other
minesweeping services would cut Pounds 1.5m.
Some amalgamation of existing facilities could be achieved, saving up to
Pounds 4m, and marine service support at Rosyth would be directed to the
base itself at a saving of Pounds 3m. There would be some job losses among
the 1,300 civilian and 1,800 naval personnel numbers to which the base will
be reduced by next April, but these would not be 'considerable'.
He said none of the minesweeper support, fishery protection work and North
Sea oil strategic support functions which the naval base performs was 'the
victim of the post-cold war changes in military requirements'. He said the
government wanted to close Rosyth both because the base was disliked by MoD
personnel and because its priority was to protect defence jobs in southern
England.
Mr Rifkind, who was visiting the Faslane submarine base on the Clyde
yesterday, hinted at a slightly enhanced role for Faslane.
He said the decision on Rosyth would be made 'in a sensitive, thoughtful
fashion'.
</TEXT>
