<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Judge's 'hands tied' on MoD plea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A judge yesterday admitted his 'hands were tied' over seven test appeals
brought by the government against large compensation awards to former
servicewomen dismissed after becoming pregnant.
Mr Justice Morison said he was aware of public disquiet over more than 2,000
awards already made against the Ministry of Defence - some of which have
been six-figure sums - but there was little he could do as far as the cases
before him were concerned.
On the final day of an Employment Appeals Tribunal in London, the judge said
his freedom to reduce the awards was limited by the way the MoD had
conducted its case. The hearing was told that an 'all or nothing' approach
had been used in making many of the original awards but the ministry had not
made that a ground of its appeal.
The judge said the tribunal could only deal with points at issue in the
appeal.
The awards came after the MoD breached European legislation by forcing
pregnant women to leave the services.
The tribunal's ruling is expected before the end of the month.
</TEXT>
