<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Tees clean-up plan threatened
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Plans for one of the UK's biggest estuary clean-up projects, intended to
help transform the Tees into a salmon river, are being reconsidered. This
follows Du Pont's announcement that it is to close five Teesside plants
acquired last year from Imperial Chemical Industries.
Northumbrian Water and ICI had proposed a Pounds 100m scheme for an effluent
treatment works on a disused ICI waste-disposal site to deal with sewage
from 400,000 Teesside residents and industrial discharges from the Wilton
petrochemicals complex, occupied by ICI and others.
The project was to be financed by Northumbrian, with ICI and other chemical
companies paying for each tonne of waste treated. It was linked to the
National River Authority's goal of bringing migratory salmon back to the
Tees by 1996.
A planning application was submitted to Cleveland County Council in May.
But the news a fortnight ago from Du Pont, the world's largest nylon maker,
that it will close five nylon intermediates plants at the Wilton site in
early 1997 has forced Northumbrian to re-evaluate the scheme's economic
feasibility. Discussions have been held between Northumbrian and ICI and the
project is now under review.
Its first Pounds 50m stage included construction of a Pounds 35m, eight-mile
underground sewer along the Tees' south bank, to discharge sewage nearer the
river mouth, from beside the Wilton site. But the cut in Du Pont effluent
resulting from the closures means pollution from the Wilton site into the
Tees will be substantially reduced, diminishing the proposed treatment
works' commercial spin-off.
Should the project be abandoned, Northumbrian is committed to reducing
pollution into the river, but the timescale will be longer.
The NRA has expressed concern this could mean the Tees may not be
re-established as a salmon fishery until the next century.
</TEXT>
