<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Inner city pupils see benefit in education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Inner-city teenagers feel positive about their education, but a third feel
they have been discriminated against, according to a report published today
by the Policy Studies Institute.
The survey, of 3,000 children of school-leaving age in east and south
London, Birmingham, Leeds, Liverpool and Manchester found that staying-on
rates in education were above the national average. About 80 per cent were
still in full-time education, compared with the national average of 68 per
cent. Only 5 per cent were in full-time employment.
School was generally regarded as useful and only 3.3 per cent admitted to
playing truant for 'weeks at a time'. But a third felt they had been treated
unfairly because of colour, sex, religion or where they lived.
There were wide disparities between ethnic groups. Black and Caribbean
pupils were most likely to truant, achieved the fewest GCSEs and were less
likely than Bangladeshis, Indians, Pakistanis or Chinese to stay on at
school. Whites made up the lowest proportion staying on - 72 per cent.
Changing Lives 1. Catherine Shaw, BEBC Distribution, PO Box 1496, Poole,
Dorset, BH12 3YD. Pounds 5.95.
</TEXT>
