<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Lloyds drops opposition to PIA watchdog
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lloyds Bank, one of the largest organisations to make public its
reservations about the personal investment authority, the new regulator to
protect the private investor, is to join the PIA after all.
The Lloyds' decision, taken at the end of last week, is a boost for the PIA
which is due to become operational on Monday. The regulator has been the
subject of controversy within the life industry, but gained from the lack of
a consensus about what should replace it.
Lloyds, which sells life insurance through its Lloyds Abbey Life arm,
entered the argument publicly in March when it said the new regulator
offered 'neither the merits of genuine self-regulation nor the settled
framework and clear accountability of regulation by a statutory body'.
The bank said yesterday that its concerns about the new regulator had not
been met, but that it felt it had no choice about joining.
It is currently regulated by Imro, the regulator for the investment
management industry. Last week, however, Imro announced a change in its
remit, aimed at excluding organisations which deal mainly with private
investors.
Lloyds' decision leaves Allied Dunbar, the life insurance subsidiary of BAT
industries, and Halifax building society, which is to set up a life
subsidiary next year, among the most high-profile organisations yet to
apply.
Allied Dunbar has had a number of discussions with the regulators, and
though there are no signs of a change in the company's direction it seems
conscious of the possible disadvantages from refusing to join the PIA.
So far only Prudential, the UK's largest life insurer, has insisted on its
right to be regulated directly by the Securities and Investments Board, the
chief financial watchdog, and has not applied to the PIA.
The PIA said yesterday that it had received almost 3,500 applications, from
a total potential membership of 5,500 to 6,000.
</TEXT>
