<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Khmer Rouge names ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Khmer Rouge guerrillas, outlawed by the Cambodian government last week after
the failure of peace talks, announced yesterday that they were establishing
a rival government based in Preah Vihear province, a jungle area on the Thai
border in the far north of the country, writes Victor Mallet in Bangkok.
According to a guerrilla radio broadcast Mr Khieu Samphan, nominal Khmer
Rouge chief, will be prime minister and defence minister in the 'provisional
government of national union and national salvation'. But Pol Pot - who
presided over the deaths of 1m Cambodians between 1975 and 1978 - is
believed to remain as real leader of the organisation.
The guerrillas control only about a tenth of Cambodian territory and depend
heavily on selling gems and timber to Thailand, but they defeated government
offensives earlier this year around Pailin in the west and Anlong Veng in
the north.
</TEXT>
