<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Murayama fails to convey stability: Gerard Baker on the
Japanese PM's performance at the G7 summit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GERARD BAKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
See Naples and die, they said, and for one awful moment on Saturday,
Japanese thought their new prime minister, Mr Tomiichi Murayama, had
interpreted the old Italian saying literally. A hastily arranged midnight
press conference during the Group of Seven summit in Naples, relayed to
Japan, hinted that the prime minister's emergency hospital visit might mean
the worst.
Within hours it emerged that the septuagenarian leader had succumbed to
nothing worse than a bout of gastroenteritis, and he was able to resume his
place at the Group of Seven talks on Sunday in the city which the old saying
implies is so beautiful there is nothing else that remains to be seen on
earth.
But as he returned home to Tokyo last night, it was clear that the meeting
had failed to resolve many of the lingering doubts about the durability of
Mr Murayama's coalition.
The government's verdict on the meeting betrayed pre-summit fears that Mr
Murayama, elected to the premiership just two weeks ago with no ministerial
experience, might not prove able to hold his own with his G7 colleagues.
'Prime minister Murayama relayed his views and ideas very frankly and
effectively through talks with the six other countries,' said Mr Kozo
Igarashi, the chief cabinet secretary.
Mr Murayama had been schooled extensively in the arts of international
relations in the days before the meeting, and there was relief that,
intestinal matters apart, he had proved up to the job.
But the more difficult task for the Japanese delegation was to convince the
other members of the G7 that the new government, principally a coalition of
the unlike-minded Social Democratic party and Liberal Democratic party,
represented both stability and continuity with its predecessors. There was
little evidence that they succeeded.
In bilateral talks with US President Bill Clinton, and later in the first
plenary session, Mr Murayama, from the SDP, and the LDP's Mr Yohei Kono, the
deputy prime minister, stressed that in the key areas of trade and security
relations the government was committed to the same goals as its
predecessors: progress would be made on the economic framework talks and the
Japan-US security relationship would remain the bulwark of Japanese foreign
policy.
The only acknowledged reservation was the role of Russia, elevated to the
status of semi-member of a G8. Foreign ministry officials were reported to
have expressed concern that Russia's presence at future political
discussions would make it difficult for Japan to use the G7 as a forum for
raising the subject of the Kurile Islands, disputed territory occupied by
Russia at the end of the second world war.
But the Japanese delegation had hardly left Naples before doubts emerged.
The unwieldy coalition seems certain to face big difficulties in maintaining
the commitments given at the G7 meeting.
The death of North Korean President Kim Il-sung presents an immediate
problem. The SDP has traditionally been friendly towards the Pyongyang
regime, and the LDP has also adopted a conciliatory stance. The uncertainty
following Mr Kim's death is likely to create strains between Japan and its
allies if, as seems likely, the government adopts a dovish approach.
But it is on economic policy that the coalition appears to be in disarray.
At the summit, Mr Murayama committed himself to continuing the pump-priming
of the economy to stimulate more imports and redress Japan's large trade
imbalances. But the SDP is anxious not to offset the large income tax cuts
implemented this year with increases in consumption tax, while the LDP and
the powerful finance ministry support an early rise in consumption tax.
As he left Naples Mr Murayama was forced to correct a misunderstanding from
an earlier statement in which he seemed to imply that Japan had agreed to
implement income tax cuts for another year, without an offsetting rise in
consumption tax.
Yesterday Mr Kiro Saito, the senior official at the finance ministry,
described as 'meaningful' the view expressed by the G7 heads of government
that exchange rates should reflect economic fundamentals, adding, 'It was
important that a common stance was reaffirmed among the summit
participants.'
The verdict of business on the summit was mixed. Mr Shoichiro Toyoda,
president of the Keidanren, the federation of economic organisations,
welcomed the meeting's call for international policy co-ordination and
structural measures for global recovery. But Mr Masaru Hayami, chairman of
the Japan Association of Corporate Executives, or Keizai Doyukai, expressed
disappointment that the summit had failed to agree on specific measures to
combat the rise of the yen on the foreign exchanges.
</TEXT>
<XX>
