<HEADLINE>
FT  12 JUL 94 / Domestic politics sets France apart on Algeria policy: Paris
finds it difficult to concur with US-led calls for dialogue with Islamic
militants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCIS GHILES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Algeria has been put back on the international agenda. Terrorism against
westerners working there was discussed at the Group of Seven summit in
Naples at the weekend, two days after six Italian sailors were killed on
board their grain ship in a harbour east of Algiers.
In the communique after the summit, the seven heads of government called
cautiously on the Algerian government to establish a dialogue with the
Islamic fundamentalists whom it outlawed when they were on the point of
winning parliamentary elections 2 1/2 years ago.
This represented a delicate compromise between the positions of France on
the one hand and the US and Italy on the other. The French are suspicious of
the American view that 'reliable and moderate' elements of the Islamic
Salvation Front (FIS) can be found for a dialogue without compromising the
current power structure of the military-led government.
Yesterday gunmen disguised as Algerian police killed four Russians and a
Romanian working with Algeria's state oil company Sonatrach.
French and American policymakers agree that, in the words of Mr Alain Juppe,
the French foreign minister, 'the status quo (in Algeria) is no longer
tenable'. And they concur that wide-ranging economic reforms are desperately
needed whatever Algeria's political fate.
However, neither Paris nor Washington rates very highly the chances of
economic reforms being implemented soon because of the political turmoil,
though both have backed the programme Algerian leaders agreed with the
International Monetary Fund in May and the Dollars 1bn standby loan which
came with it. And both supported the rescheduling of Dollars 5bn worth of
Algeria's Dollars 26bn (Pounds 17bn) foreign debt by the country's Paris
Club official creditors.
Beyond that, however, the two capitals appear to be drawing different
conclusions from the failure of all attempts so far to bring to the
negotiating table Algeria's military commanders and the leaders of the FIS.
The difference between the US and French positions is that while Washington
is attempting to build a long-term strategy towards a political force which
it is convinced is here to stay, French leaders, who privately agree that
political Islam will not disappear overnight, feel constrained by domestic
considerations.
US officials say they are trying to avoid 'demonising' supporters of the
FIS, a party which Mr Juppe describes as 'extremist, terrorist,
anti-European and anti-western'.
French politicians, on the other hand, are caught in a bind. While they
acknowledge the present political system is not viable, what conservative
politicians fear above all is the fundamentalists either sharing power with
the military or seizing power in the run-up to the French presidential
election next year. As they see it, such an event would draw the issue of
Algeria, radical Islam and perhaps France's 2m immigrants of North African
extraction into the election campaign and boost the vote for far-right
politicians such as Mr Jean-Marie le Pen.
French officials also fear the domino effect of a FIS takeover in Algeria.
Some go as far as to argue that Tunisia would 'fall in six months' and that
Morocco and Egypt would quickly be threatened.
In a joint television interview with President Francois Mitterrand last
month, President Bill Clinton made clear that while he shared the concern of
Paris about a fundamentalist takeover spreading unrest in the Moslem world,
the US would encourage 'the present Algerian government to broaden its base
(and) reach out to dissident groups who are not involved in terrorism'.
US policymakers have sought to draw on the lessons learned from their
country's long estrangement from Iran, as well as from Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait and the strong anti-western feelings it provoked in Arab public
opinion. They note that 17 of the 22 Moslem states have falling incomes and
a predominantly youthful population. 'The potential for explosion is great,'
they warn.
The conclusions were summed up recently by Mr Robert Pelletreau, the US
assistant secretary of state for near-eastern affairs:
'The US does not view Islam as the next 'ism' confronting the west, or
threatening world peace, but does however, object strongly when the US is
labelled a great Satan.'
The US is 'suspicious of those who would use the democratic process to come
to power, only to destroy that process in order to retain political
dominance', a clear reference to the FIS assertion that a victory at the
polls would only prove Allah's greatness, thus making the holding of any
future election a pointless exercise.
While concerned at the role of Iran and Sudan in exploiting Islamic
extremist groups, the US sees 'no monolithic international control being
exercised over the various Islamic movements active in the region'.
While it does not wish to impose a western model of government in the Middle
East, the US believes that broad political participation is 'an important
and necessary contributor to long-term stability. Lack of economic,
educational and political opportunities (are what) give extremists of any
sort their constituency'.
European and US officials also note that French support for reforms in
Algeria is a recent development and occurred just before the Socialists lost
their majority in the French parliament last year. French conservative
politicians acknowledge this and say that not supporting Algerian political
leaders who sought to implement bold economic reforms between 1989 and 1992
was a grievous mistake.
French support, albeit qualified, for the current Algerian leadership is
based on a belief shared by Mr Charles Pasqua, the powerful interior
minister, and Mr Juppe that a FIS victory would spell trouble among the
large Algerian and broader North African community in France. Some French
observers say the high level of unemployment among young North Africans, as
much as 50 per cent in some areas, is a more serious threat to social and
political peace than events across the Mediterranean. Officials in Paris
also say they fear an influx of refugees were the FIS to win power.
Some European countries, notably Spain and Germany, are concerned that while
the acts of terrorism committed by supporters of radical Islam are
repeatedly denounced abroad, the methods used by the security forces, which
are increasingly brutal, are seldom mentioned. They believe that the
European Union has much to gain in the medium run by being more even-handed.
France's key European partner, Germany, the current EU president, needs
France's support on east European affairs and has little to gain by
questioning the support Paris is lending the Algerian regime. Italy and
Spain have their own domestic political difficulties and Madrid is unhappy
about the public expression of divergences between the US and France on
Algeria policy.
French officials agree with their European and US colleagues that most of
those who support the FIS do so out of despair at the lack of jobs,
corruption and contempt for their leaders. They also suspect that the
Clinton administration is hedging its bets by initiating contacts with FIS
representatives abroad but acknowledge that US strategic interests in the
Middle East include Israel, Egypt and Saudi Arabia, not Algeria.
</TEXT>
<XX>
